    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2720172775" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2720172775" />
    <a title="Becky" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10432110-becky"><img alt="Becky" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1487782357p2/10432110.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2720172775?book_show_action=true">Feb 07, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Becky" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Becky" href="/user/show/10432110-becky">Becky</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2720172775" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6091675394948983514">I’ve been looking forward to reading Maryse Condé for ages, and I always wanted to start with this title: I, Tituba, Black Witch of Salem (translated from French by Condé’s husband, Richard Philcox). This book did not disappoint. It’s a fictional exposition of the real life of Tituba, an enslaved woman who was the first person accused of witchcraft during the 1692 Salem witch trials. She was imprisoned for over a year after confessing to her “crimes” under duress, and then was once again enslave</span>
  <span id="freeText6091675394948983514" style="display:none">I’ve been looking forward to reading Maryse Condé for ages, and I always wanted to start with this title: I, Tituba, Black Witch of Salem (translated from French by Condé’s husband, Richard Philcox). This book did not disappoint. It’s a fictional exposition of the real life of Tituba, an enslaved woman who was the first person accused of witchcraft during the 1692 Salem witch trials. She was imprisoned for over a year after confessing to her “crimes” under duress, and then was once again enslaved. I understand that Condé did much research about the historical Tituba in the writing of this novel, however not much is known about her origins or what happened after her fleeting mentions in the records of the trials, so these portions of the narrative are invented by Condé. I enjoyed reading this book and found it hard to put down despite the heavy topics, I think because Condé isn’t taking the story in a wholly serious direction. It goes some surprising places, such as the introduction of The Scarlet Letter’s protagonist Hester as a companion to Tituba in prison. Condé’s Tituba is a great character and I’m glad to have been introduced to her through this rendition, although I am interested to read Ann Petry’s children’s book, Tituba of Salem Village too. (Condé speaks somewhat dismissively about the choice to write Tituba into a set of life lessons for kids, but I’m still curious to read Petry’s take.) So glad I read this one and I’m looking forward to reading more of Condé’s work!</span>
  <a data-text-id="6091675394948983514" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


