<div id="review_125066112" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/125066112" />
    <a title="Silver" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1430273-silver"><img alt="Silver" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1218844161p2/1430273.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/125066112?book_show_action=true">Oct 06, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Silver" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Silver" href="/user/show/1430273-silver">Silver</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1430273-silver?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer125066112" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11711840914411776614">I am fascinated with the Salem Witch trails and I loved the Crucible, one of my favorite characters from the Crucible was Tituba, though she did not play a very large role, I always found her quite intriguing so I loved the concept of this book and was quite excited about it. <br/><br/>After reading it I am left with mix feelings. On the one hand it was interesting to see things from the persepctive and to watch how things unraveled from an outsiders point of view and it was also interesting seeing the wa</span>
  <span id="freeText11711840914411776614" style="display:none">I am fascinated with the Salem Witch trails and I loved the Crucible, one of my favorite characters from the Crucible was Tituba, though she did not play a very large role, I always found her quite intriguing so I loved the concept of this book and was quite excited about it. <br /><br />After reading it I am left with mix feelings. On the one hand it was interesting to see things from the persepctive and to watch how things unraveled from an outsiders point of view and it was also interesting seeing the way in which the issue of slavery played into events. I also liked the way in which the supernatural and realism played together within the book. But one of the things I found disappointing about the book is that I would have liked to have seen more of the actual witch trails themselves. It felt to me that the trails themselves did not play a prominent enough role within the book, of course part of the reason for this is becasue we are seeing the story from Tituba's point of view, and being she spent a great deal of time during the trails imprisoned the reader is only subject to the information which she possess. Though one of the most interesting aspects of the book was the fact that it included an excerpt from transcripts of the real Tituba's actual testimony during the trails. <br /><br />One of the other major complaints I had about the book is that it felt to me that in the middle of the book it sort of moved away too much from the story itself, as the author I think tried to hard to hit the reader over the head with both a feminist and racial message behind the story, and she stepped out of the time period in which the story was being told and introduced modern ideas. She also gave Titbua a sort of "prophetic" voice in which she spoke back upon the witch trails from a modern point of view, as if the author herself was speaking through Titbua, as she spoke of events of things that were not yet to happen within the setting of the story itself, and it felt out of place in the story and did not really work. It was too much like trying to enclose a lecture on the witch trials within the story. <br /><br />But towards the end of the book it started to pick up against and become more interesting, and over all I really did enjoy it and I really enjoyed the parts of the book which dealt with the culture of Barbados, which is another area of interest of mine, and where Titbua is said within the book to have originally came from. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11711840914411776614" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

